    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Congratulations on your first home purchase! Escrow is a crucial process, and I'm happy to explain it to you. The earnest money deposit, also known as the earnest money, is a good faith payment made by you to the seller when you make an offer on the property. It's typically held in an escrow account, which is a separate bank account managed by the escrow agent or title company. The escrow agent holds the earnest money until the closing date, when it's released to the seller as part of the transaction.\n\nThink of the earnest money like a down payment on a trust – it's a promise to the seller that you're committed to the purchase, and it's held in escrow until the deal is finalized. The escrow agent will typically hold the earnest money in a separate account, and it may earn interest until the closing date. Once the closing is complete, the earnest money is released to the seller, and you'll receive a refund of any remaining balance in your earnest money deposit.\n\nIt's worth noting that the earnest money deposit is usually non-refundable if the sale falls through, but this can vary depending on the terms of the sale agreement and the local laws. Your realtor should be able to",
